    "body": "I've tested with that many wallets, by using mainnet forking and hardhat_impersonateAccount.  e.g.\r\n\r\n```\r\nasync function impersonate(account: string): Promise<SignerWithAddress> {\r\n    await ethers.provider.send(\"hardhat_impersonateAccount\", [account]);\r\n    return ethers.getSigner(account)\r\n}\r\n```\r\n\r\nThen in the test you can use the method like this:\r\n\r\n```\r\n const onlyOwner = \"Ownable: caller is not the owner\"\r\n const { hacker } = await getNamedAccounts() // This is an example from .namedAccounts in hardhat.config\r\n const impersonatedSigner = await impersonate(hacker)\r\n await expect(myContract.connect(impersonatedSigner).someMethod()).to.be.revertedWith(onlyOwner)\r\n ```\r\n\r\n In the example above, instead of `hacker` you can put in any public address, including those that are visible from mainnet via forking. This works only in tests, however\r\n \r\n If these accounts need additional money, you can send ETH from one of the 10 hardhat accounts. Here's my method for doing that from the first account:\r\n \r\n ```\r\n async function sendEth(ether: number, address: string): Promise<TransactionResponse> {\r\n    const accounts = await ethers.getSigners()\r\n    const signer = accounts[0]\r\n    return signer.sendTransaction({ to: address, value: ethers.utils.parseEther(ether.toString()) })\r\n}\r\n ```",
